📏 CSS Units — What & Why

CSS units decide how big or small elements and text appear.

Two main types:

Absolute units → fixed size

Relative units → responsive (based on something)

🔴 Absolute Units (fixed)

These do NOT change with screen size.

✅ px (most common)
.box {
width: 200px;
font-size: 16px;
}

✔ Features

Fixed size

Easy to use

Not responsive

👉 Use for: borders, icons, small fixed items

🟢 Relative Units (VERY IMPORTANT)

These change based on parent/root/screen.

✅ % (percentage)

Relative to parent size

.parent {
width: 400px;
}

.child {
width: 50%;
}

👉 Child becomes 200px

✅ em

Relative to parent font-size

.parent {
font-size: 20px;
}

.child {
font-size: 2em; /_ 40px _/
}

⚠️ Warning

em can compound (multiply again and again).

✅ rem ⭐ (MOST IMPORTANT)

Relative to root (html) font-size

html {
font-size: 16px;
}

h1 {
font-size: 2rem; /_ 32px _/
}

✔ Why rem is best

predictable

scalable

industry standard

👉 Use rem for fonts

✅ vh (viewport height)

Relative to screen height

.hero {
height: 100vh;
}

👉 Full screen section

✅ vw (viewport width)

Relative to screen width

.box {
width: 50vw;
}

🧠 Quick Memory Trick
Unit Based on
px fixed
% parent
em parent font
rem root font ⭐
vh screen height
vw screen width
🧪 Mini Practice (do this)
HTML

<div class="parent">
	<div class="child">Resize me</div>
</div>

CSS
.parent {
width: 400px;
background: lightgray;
}

.child {
width: 50%;
background: lightblue;
}

👉 Resize window and observe.

🎯 Real-world usage guide

✅ Fonts → rem
✅ Layout width → % or vw
✅ Full screen section → vh
✅ Small fixed things → px

🗣️ Viva one-liner

“CSS units control sizing, where px is fixed and rem, %, vh, vw are responsive units.”
